Oh God, if you're impressed with me this far, let me tell the story.

01:18.118 --> 01:23.245
Let me get a coffee and I'll tell you the story.

01:25.064 --> 01:32.371
But in fact, I have the preferences again by saying I'm not obsessed by this thing that happened 23 years ago.

01:32.391 --> 01:37.075
It was just the kind of key under the mattress that got me started.

01:37.756 --> 01:45.463
I came in the right one day and I was researching through old newspapers for something historical.

01:45.563 --> 01:50.228
I had an idea I was going to do an article for something.

01:50.508 --> 01:54.632
So I went up to the microfiche and a couple of kids came up and they must have been about 10.

01:55.439 --> 02:00.984
And I remember there were three of them.

02:01.004 --> 02:10.594
And I was kind of casually dressed, so they kind of looked over my shoulder, and they said, hey, mister, what are you doing?

02:10.614 --> 02:11.715
And I said, well, I'm looking for something.

02:11.955 --> 02:13.697
And I showed them.

02:14.778 --> 02:15.559
And actually, yeah, microphone.

02:15.579 --> 02:24.347
And if you remember, all the newspapers are fascinating because they're so different from the way they are now.

02:24.367 --> 02:25.328
The cartoons are all different.

02:25.848 --> 02:36.221
In those days, they have pictures of all the brides, wedding announcements, things like that, which is really fascinating because you see a different world.

02:37.803 --> 02:40.907
So I said to one of these kids, when were you born?

02:41.208 --> 02:44.011
You know, it's really nice to look at a newspaper at the day you were born.

02:44.792 --> 02:54.505
So I said, you know, just go this thing out and put the date and take it to that person over there and we'll set this thing out and we'll show the newspaper the day you were born.

02:55.244 --> 02:58.067
And the kids thought that was cool.

03:00.869 --> 03:03.732
The kids thought that was cool.

03:03.812 --> 03:14.502
So a janitor comes along and unplugs their machine.

03:14.522 --> 03:18.586
And I looked at this guy and he said, you're just playing.

03:18.606 --> 03:21.609
He unplugged the kids' machine, not my machine.

03:21.629 --> 03:22.210
I was back to doing my thing.

03:23.471 --> 03:24.812
And so he unplugged the kids' machine and said,

03:25.282 --> 03:27.391
that you're not serious, you're just playing.

03:27.993 --> 03:31.989
Well, at that point, he's making an intellectual judgment.

03:32.009 --> 03:33.355
He's making a judgment.

03:33.375 --> 03:34.600
He was making a judgment.

03:35.373 --> 03:39.919
about something I consider very basic, which is intellectual curiosity.

03:39.939 --> 03:41.361
You know, you don't need a reason.

03:41.922 --> 03:45.446
Well, I totally agree with you.

03:45.466 --> 03:45.687
Guess what?

03:45.707 --> 03:46.247
Guess what?

03:46.287 --> 03:47.709
We don't have a topic here.

03:47.829 --> 03:50.453
So at that point, I was pretty secure in my ground, right?

03:50.473 --> 03:54.138
